quran[5]{c,v,t,f}:
  33,31,"But whoever of you is devout towards Allah and His Messenger and acts righteously—We{1}will bring her her reward twice over, and We have prepared for her a noble provision.",footnotes:1:[Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…He will bring her her reward…”]
  33,32,"O wives of the Prophet, you are not like any of the other women. If you are truly mindful<i>(of God) </i>, then do not speak too softly, lest the sick at heart lust after you, but speak forthright words."
  33,33,"And settle{1}in your houses and do not display yourselves as in the former days of pagan ignorance, and establish the prayer and bring{2}the purifying charity{3}and obey Allah and His Messenger; indeed, Allah only wants to keep abomination away from you, O people of the<i>(Prophet’s) </i>household, and to cleanse you thoroughly.",footnotes:1:[Qira’at: All except for Nafie’, Asem and Abu Ja’far read it as: “And settle, revered, in your houses…”],footnotes:2:[The Qur’an always uses verb ‘to bring’ rather than verb ‘to give’ in association with charity; this should be pondered by the reader.],footnotes:3:[The Arabic word used is <i>zakāt</i>, which denotes purification and growth.]
  33,34,"And remember what is recited in your{1}houses of Allah’s signs{2}, and wisdom; indeed, Allah has always been Subtle, All-Aware.",footnotes:1:[Plural feminine possessive adjective denoting that once again the addressed are the wives of the Prophet (peace be upon him).],footnotes:2:[The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.]
  33,35,"Indeed, Muslim men and Muslim women, and believing men and believing women, and devout men and devout women, and truthful men and truthful women, and patient men and patient women, and reverent men and reverent women, and charitable men and charitable women, and fasting men and fasting women, and men who preserve their private parts{1}and women who<i>(likewise) </i>preserve, and men who remember Allah frequently and women who<i>(likewise) </i>remember—Allah has prepared for them forgiveness and a great reward.",footnotes:1:[A metaphor for chastity.]
